book.preface:
&reftitle.intro;
The Output Control functions allow you to control when output is sent from the script. This can be useful in several different situations, especially if you need to send headers to the browser after your script has began outputting data. The Output Control functions do not affect headers sent using header or setcookie, only functions such as echo and data between blocks of PHP code.
When upgrading from PHP 4.1.x (and 4.2.x) to 4.3.x due to a bug in earlier versions you must ensure that implict_flush is OFF in your &php.ini;, otherwise any output with ob_start will not be hidden from output.

book.appendix:
   &reftitle.examples;


   &reftitle.examples;



     Output Control example


<?php

ob_start();
echo "Hello\n";

setcookie("cookiename", "cookiedata");

ob_end_flush();

?>






    In the above example, the output from echo
    would be stored in the output buffer until
    ob_end_flush was called. In the mean time,
    the call to setcookie successfully stored a
    cookie without causing an error. (You can not normally send
    headers to the browser after data has already been sent.)
